## Command Chain During Operations

### **Normal Operations**
```
CHIEF â†’ SR Operators â†’ Operators â†’ Analysts/Techs
```

### **Shift Operations**
```
SHIFT SUPERVISOR â†’ All Operators on duty
(Supervisor has oversight but SR maintains technical authority)
```

### **Emergency Response**
```
CHIEF â†’ SHIFT SUPERVISOR â†’ All available CRITICAL/HIGH personnel
(IT and Engineering support as needed)
```

### **Field Coordination**
```
SR Operators â†’ Field Technicians â†’ Maintenance Technicians
(Direct communication via radio/phone for real-time issues)
```

---

## Key Observations for Attack Simulation

### **High-Value Targets (HVTs)**
1. **David Chen (PSE-001)** - Master control over all systems
2. **Sarah Kim (PSE-004)** - Can create/modify authentication
3. **Laura Martinez (PSE-020)** - Emergency override capabilities
4. **Linda Martinez (PSE-010)** - Can alter historical data

### **Privilege Escalation Paths**
```
IT Admin â†’ Network Access â†’ Token Creation â†’ SCADA Control
Field Tech â†’ Physical Access â†’ Rogue Device â†’ System Compromise
Junior Engineer â†’ Supervised Access â†’ Credential Theft â†’ Unauthorized Changes
```

### **Lateral Movement Opportunities**
- Operators share similar access levels â†’ Token reuse across sectors
- Field techs have both remote AND physical access
- Shift supervisor can override normal restrictions

### **Single Points of Failure**
- Only 1 Chief SCADA Engineer (no immediate backup)
- Only 1 SCADA Systems Admin (controls all authentication)
- Limited separation between IT infrastructure and SCADA operations

